<HEADLINE>
Less Sugar, More Fiber
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the same week the government released new exercise and nutrition
guidelines, food processors took steps to put themselves on the right
side of the national campaign against obesity. Companies rolled out
new versions of popular items, such as Cocoa Puffs and chocolate
syrup, that have less sugar and salt and offer more vitamins and whole
grains. Kraft Foods, maker of Oreos, Kool-Aid and Oscar Mayer lunch
meats, said it will curb radio and television advertising aimed at
children under 12.
</P>
